This scene features a surprise, uncredited cameo from George Clooney as Doug Ross. He agreed to return at scale pay (minimum wage) as long as his return was not used to publicize the episode. As a result, the final scene where Carol and Doug see each other was not originally part of the episode, and was added on at the very last minute so that NBC didn't have time to realize what was happening before the episode aired.

title: New Pediatric ER at Shands will enhance emergency care for children
description:
Children are not small adults. This is never more evident than when an accident or urgent medical problem arises and parents need fast access to specialized care designed to meet their child's needs.

On July 1, the new Pediatric Emergency Room at Shands Hospital for Children at the University of Florida will open, becoming north central Florida's first emergency room specifically geared toward kids.

Located at Shands at the University of Florida, the Pediatric ER will have a separate entrance with free valet parking for adults transporting children, and an adjacent parking garage for visitors. Calming, child-friendly dÃ©cor with a nautical theme enhances the check-in and waiting areas, with porthole windows, saltwater aquariums and floors made to look like waves adding to the atmosphere.

More important, families will have access to an expanded team of UF pediatric emergency medicine physicians and Shands pediatric emergency-trained nurses, additional treatment space and the latest medical technology.

"This new Pediatric ER benefits our patients and our UF&Shands teams," said Jennifer Light, M.D., UF College of Medicine clinical assistant professor of emergency medicine and Pediatric ER medical director. "We've created an environment just for families, staffed by people committed to the care of children. This generates great positive energy and the opportunity for us to improve services and the whole experience for young patients and their families."

The Pediatric ER will be staffed by seven UF board-certified or board-eligible pediatric emergency medicine physicians and 22 Shands pediatric-trained emergency medicine registered nurses. The team will be able to treat up to 24,000 pediatric emergency patients a year.

title: ER Realities - 24 Hours in A&E - Medical Documentary
description:
24 Hours in A&E - S02 E02

Embark on a gripping journey through the bustling King's College Hospital Trauma Centre in London. Witness the relentless efforts of medical professionals as they tackle diverse critical cases, from a pregnant woman's distress to a young rider's unexplained injury. Experience the emotional whirlwind of life and death, the resilience of patients and their families, and the challenges faced by dedicated doctors. This insightful episode provides an inside perspective on the highs and lows of emergency medicine.

-------

24 Hours in A&E is a British documentary series that takes viewers on an emotionally charged journey into the heart of a busy trauma center. This gripping reality TV show provides an unfiltered and compelling look at the daily workings of a UK healthcare system, specifically the emergency department of a hospital.

With a focus on patient care and critical care, 24 Hours in A&E showcases the true essence of hospital life and the incredible work of medical professionals. Through real-life medical cases and patient stories, the show offers an honest and raw depiction of medical emergencies and the crucial medical treatment needed to save lives.

Filmed in real-time, the documentary offers an unscripted and captivating look at the fast-paced environment of an emergency room. The show explores the human interest aspect of healthcare, portraying the personal lives of the patients and their families as they navigate through life-changing medical situations.

A&E documentary, medical documentary, and hospital documentary all rolled into one, 24 Hours in A&E offers a unique perspective on the reality of emergency medicine. Broadcast on Channel 4, this real-life medical drama has become a critically acclaimed hospital reality TV show, gaining popularity for its powerful and touching portrayal of the human spirit in times of crisis.

Overall, 24 Hours in A&E is a must-watch for anyone interested in medical emergencies, UK healthcare, and the incredible work of medical professionals in the emergency department.

Step into the fast-paced world of King's College Hospital's ER. title: I chose emergency medicine bc the ER is a safety net for vulnerable patients #postshiftmusings
description:
I chose to go into emergency medicine because I have a strong commitment to serving our society's poorest and most vulnerable communities. The ER is often the only place that these patients can access healthcare. There are many times that we as clinicians have to take extra time in order to provide the detailed care that our most vulnerable patients deserve. Even in the moments that this feels burdensome, I always re-center my mind and remind myself that this is precisely why I wanted to come into this field.ï¿¼ï¿¼

title: Part 1 - My Trip to the ER (Emergency Room) - Life with Jessica (mostly Spanish video)
description:
Hi guys, As you see, this isn't my typical "English" video. Well, it's really not an English video at all, but about me and my health issues. I've been suffering from chronic (non-stop) lower back pain for over two years now and I can't handle it anymore. I'm changing the way SELVA is done to comply my new lifestyle. I hope you like it and enjoy this journey with me and learn English while you do it!

Will I still make more English lessons like grammar and recommendations? 

Yes, of course. I love teaching...especially grammar, but in order for me to understand how to teach you grammar it takes a lot of thinking on my end and I'm just not capable right now (mostly due to my lack of sleep). If you'd like more structured English lessons, I recommend JenniferESL. She is always professional. 

In this video I am completely wacked out. I had several severe side effects from a new medicine, Cymbalta, that the doctor put me on to see if it would help my pain. It did...I was pain free for about two hours the day I filmed this video, but it's also the last day I took the medicine that was sending me into mania....literally. 

My mama said that this isn't "me" in the video. But it is me...I'm just sick. She advised me not to post these three videos, but I feel strongly about the need to NOT be private about my health anymore. I was always so scared to get the healthcare I needed...that is...until I couldn't put it off (wait) any longer. 

When I found out I was depressed and had social anxiety (not on video, thank goodness) I started taking Paxil and it has honestly changed my life. I feel like I gained ten years of maturity in just a few months. I'm not advocating taking drugs. What I am doing is speaking up about getting the help you need.

title:
Behind the Scenes: 12 Hours in the ER
#emergency room visit
description:
A Day in the Life: #EmergencyMedicine

"Join me as I navigate through a particularly intense shift in the emergency department. This day was filled with a myriad of cases - from managing an elderly patient with altered consciousness to handling a critical cardiac arrest case. 

We start with the admission of an elderly woman, whose consciousness did not improve despite our best efforts, necessitating intubation. This was followed by a highly urgent situation - a patient brought in with a cardiac arrest due to opium poisoning. Despite our resuscitation efforts, we tragically weren't able to save them.

Later in the day, we encountered a patient suffering from ventricular arrhythmia and palpitations, a serious condition that required quick action. With the administration of two timely shocks, we were able to stabilize them.

This video provides a snapshot of the challenging and unpredictable nature of working in an emergency room. The rapid pace, the life-or-death decisions, and the sheer variety of cases we handle are what makes this job both extremely demanding and incredibly rewarding.

How Common are Emergency Room Mistakes? #accidentlawyer #legalhelpmiami #accidentlawyermiami
description:
ER Mistakes: A Closer Look at Miami Hospitals
Emergency rooms are vital for urgent care, but even in Miami's renowned medical centers, mistakes can happen. While most ER visits go smoothly, data shows that errors are more common than you might think:
Misdiagnosis: Studies suggest 5.7% of all ER visits nationwide involve misdiagnosis, affecting over 7 million patients annually. This is a particular concern in Miami, where the fast pace of ERs can sometimes lead to rushed decisions.
Medication Errors: These occur in approximately 6.7% of hospitalized patients, potentially causing adverse drug events, allergic reactions, and even death.
Delayed Treatment: A 2023 study found average ER wait times in Miami exceeding 2 hours, raising concerns about patients not receiving timely care for critical conditions.
Know Your Rights as a Patient
If you or a loved one believe you've been harmed due to an ER error in a Miami hospital, it's important to understand your rights. You may be entitled to compensation for medical expenses, lost wages, and pain and suffering.

Julian Xane Phillips Rendition of Brian Reganâ€™s - ER Emergency Room
description:
Julian is our son, and he got a kidney transplant when he was three. He is on the Spectrum for Autism, and this is somewhat of a Speech Therapy/Occupational Therapy for him. We went on a cruise to the Bahamas last week and found an empty stage/room mid-day. Hereâ€™s what happened! Love this boy!

Julian gives a bit of stand-up humor â€œborrowedâ€ from Brian Regan on stage on the Carnival Liberty. It was mid-day and I was his only audience. This is from Brian Reganâ€™s â€œI Walked in the Moonâ€ Comedy Show, and is Julianâ€™s rendition of the Emergency Room or ER. When we took Julian TO the ER 6 months ago for anemia, he watched that portion over and over, he laughed and laughed, and it made the 6 hour stay more enjoyable. 

*I do not own the rights to this original Brian Regan material, it is a â€œcoverâ€ impersonation performance and he had zero audience except me (his mom), and this brought me great joy so I wanted to share it. Hopefully it can inspire children and adults who are on the Autism Spectrum and raise awareness for how unique and special each individual on the planet truly is.

Brian Regan is one of Julianâ€™s heroes, and we just bought tickets to see him on Dec 31st 2019 in Phoenix. If you see this, Brian, please wave at Julian, heâ€™ll be in Section 8, seat 3 or 4! Lol!

Live from the ER - Emergency Room is my Consequence for NOT being Present
description:
Today marks my loss to the inner battle of being Present, staying focused and positive in the moment.

I was too in my head over thinking and mindlessly walked too fast down the stairs.

Slipped fucked up my body my back, ribs, and pacemaker all flared up in crazy sharp pains, came to ER to get everything checked out.

I will get back up on my feet and fight another day tomorrow, with more Breath, taking life moment to moment, in Gratitude, and Presence of mind.

Gratefully the Docs conclude I strained and bruised my rib, chest and back muscles. Structurally everything looks sound and no internal bleeding, breaks, or rips.

Thank you God.

This is the "ER" tv-set at the Warner Brothers Studios in Burbank. ER is an American medical drama television series created by novelist and physician Michael Crichton that aired on NBC from September 19, 1994, to April 2, 2009, with a total of 331 episodes spanning 15 seasons. It was produced by Constant C Productions and Amblin Television, in association with Warner Bros. Television. ER follows the inner life of the emergency room (ER) of Cook County General Hospital (a fictionalized version of the real Cook County Hospital) in Chicago, Illinois, and various critical issues faced by the department's physicians and staff.
